### 4.3 `framework/session` — New Package

Session boundary enforcement is a security invariant. This package validates that agents only access sessions they are authorized for, and routes inbound messages to the correct session boundary.

```go
package session

// Router routes inbound messages to session boundaries using scope policy.
type Router interface {
    // Route resolves the SessionBoundary for an inbound message.
    // The scope is determined by the active PolicyEngine.
    Route(ctx context.Context, msg InboundMessage) (*core.SessionBoundary, error)

    // Authorize checks whether an actor may access a session.
    // Returns an error if the session boundary is violated.
    Authorize(ctx context.Context, actorID string, boundary *core.SessionBoundary) error
}

// InboundMessage is the normalized input to the session router.
type InboundMessage struct {
    Partition  string
    ChannelID  string
    PeerID     string
    ThreadID   string
    ActorID    string
    TrustClass core.TrustClass
}

// Store persists session boundaries and state.
type Store interface {
    GetBoundary(ctx context.Context, key string) (*core.SessionBoundary, error)
    UpsertBoundary(ctx context.Context, boundary *core.SessionBoundary) error
    ListBoundaries(ctx context.Context, partition string) ([]core.SessionBoundary, error)
    DeleteBoundary(ctx context.Context, key string) error
}

// DefaultRouter is the standard implementation of Router.
// It uses the PolicyEngine to determine scope and enforces:
// - TrustClass of the session's originating identity
// - Partition isolation (no cross-partition access)
// - Actor authorization (agents cannot access sessions they were not
//   granted access to, regardless of application routing)
type DefaultRouter struct {
    Policy  runtime.PolicyEngine
    Store   Store
    Log     event.Log
    Scope   core.SessionScope  // default scope, overridable by policy
}
```

**Security invariant:** `Authorize` must be called before any agent reads session history. This is enforced in the framework's `AgentFacingAPI` implementation, not left to application code.

