### 4.5 `framework/runtime` — PolicyEngine Promotion

The existing `PermissionManager` (`Ask/Allow/Deny` per-tool) is **not replaced** — it is wrapped and surfaced as a `PolicyEngine` that also evaluates `PolicyRule` sets.

This is backward-compatible: existing agent manifests with `default_tool_policy: ask` and per-tool policies continue to work. They are translated to `PolicyRule` entries by the runtime.

```go
package runtime

// PolicyEngine evaluates declarative policy rules.
// Satisfies the broader policy interface needed by session, node, and capability layers.
type PolicyEngine interface {
    // Evaluate returns the policy decision for a given request.
    // Default (no rules match): deny.
    Evaluate(ctx context.Context, req core.PolicyRequest) (core.PolicyDecision, error)

    // Load replaces the active rule set.
    Load(rules []core.PolicyRule) error

    // Reload hot-reloads rules from the configured source (manifest, file).
    Reload(ctx context.Context) error

    // ApproveHITL resolves a pending approval request.
    ApproveHITL(ctx context.Context, requestID string, scope GrantScope) error

    // DenyHITL denies a pending approval request.
    DenyHITL(ctx context.Context, requestID string) error
}

// DefaultPolicyEngine wraps PermissionManager and evaluates PolicyRule sets.
// Priority order: explicit PolicyRule match → PermissionManager tool policy → default.
type DefaultPolicyEngine struct {
    rules      []core.PolicyRule
    manager    *PermissionManager  // existing, for backward compat
    log        event.Log           // logs policy.evaluated.v1 events
    hitlQueue  map[string]*HITLRequest
}

func NewDefaultPolicyEngine(manager *PermissionManager, log event.Log) *DefaultPolicyEngine

// FromManifest builds a DefaultPolicyEngine from an agent manifest.
// Translates manifest tool_execution_policy and default_tool_policy
// entries to PolicyRule objects.
func FromManifest(manifest *manifest.AgentManifest, log event.Log) (*DefaultPolicyEngine, error)
```

