## 7. Agent Runtime Integration with Nexus

### 7.1 Relurpify as an Agent Client

When a Nexus gateway is running, Relurpify connects as a client with `role: agent`. The connection is optional — the agent runs fully standalone if no gateway is configured.

```go
// In app/relurpish/runtime/runtime.go (add NexusConfig)
type NexusConfig struct {
    Enabled    bool   `yaml:"enabled"`
    Address    string `yaml:"address"`    // e.g. "ws://localhost:18789"
    Token      string `yaml:"token"`
    AutoReconnect bool `yaml:"auto_reconnect"`
}
```

When connected, the agent:
1. Subscribes to `session.message.v1` events routed to its session.
2. Invokes capabilities via the `AgentFacingAPI` (which routes to nodes via the gateway).
3. Sends responses back through the gateway (which delivers to the originating channel).

The `CapabilityRegistry` in the agent runtime registers a `ProviderKindAgentRuntime` provider wrapping the Nexus WS connection. Capabilities advertised by the gateway (from connected nodes) are registered locally as `RuntimeFamilyProvider` entries. The agent code is unaware of the difference — it just calls `registry.Invoke(ctx, "camera.capture", args, state)`.

### 7.2 Agent Observability via Event Log (Assumption A2)

Even without Nexus, agent runs emit events to the local SQLite event log (`relurpify_cfg/events.db`, partition `local`). This enables:

- **Replay debugging:** step through exactly what the agent did, in order, for any run.
- **Audit trail:** full record of every tool call, LLM request, HITL decision.
- **Test assertions:** integration tests can assert on the event sequence, not just the final output.

Instrumentation points in the existing code:

| Location | Event emitted |
|---|---|
| `agents/pattern/react.go` `reactThinkNode` | `llm.requested.v1`, `llm.responded.v1` |
| `agents/pattern/react.go` `reactActNode` | `capability.invoked.v1`, `capability.result.v1` |
| `framework/runtime/hitl.go` | `hitl.requested.v1`, `hitl.resolved.v1` |
| `framework/runtime/permissions.go` `AuthorizeTool` | `policy.evaluated.v1` |
| `agents/coding_agent.go` `Execute` | `agent.run.started.v1`, `agent.run.completed.v1` |

The `event.Log` is wired into agents via `core.Config`:

```go
// Add to framework/core/context.go or core config
type Config struct {
    // ... existing fields ...
    EventLog event.Log  // nil = no event logging (backward compat)
}
```

### 7.3 Relurpify as a Nexus Node (Assumption A3 — Opt-in)

When `node_registration.enabled: true` in config, the running Relurpify process registers itself as a `ProviderKindNodeDevice` with `NodePlatformLinux|MacOS|Headless`. It exposes its `framework/capability` registry back to the Nexus gateway, making local tools (file read/write, shell exec, LSP, etc.) available to other agents connected to the same gateway.

This is explicitly opt-in. The default is standalone operation with no Nexus dependency.

